9 Analysis and synthesis

library(grassland)

Analyze individual species contributing to CTI-CPI change

Calculate the trend in abundance of species over time at the observational sites or under warming treatment in the experiment.

dat_gainloss <- calc_species_gainloss(dat_community = dat_community, dat_niche = dat_niche)
usethis::use_data(dat_gainloss, overwrite = T)
gg_gainloss_elkhorn1 <- plot_species_gainloss_obs(
  obs_tbl = dat_gainloss$obs %>%
    mutate(
      change = "no clear change",
      complete_change = NA
    ),
  dat_niche, onesite = "elkhorn"
)$circle
gg_gainloss_elkhorn2 <- plot_species_gainloss_obs(
  obs_tbl = dat_gainloss$obs %>%
    mutate(
      change = if_else(change == "increase", "increase", "no clear change"),
      complete_change = NA
    ),
  dat_niche, onesite = "elkhorn"
)$circle
gg_gainloss_elkhorn3 <- plot_species_gainloss_obs(
  obs_tbl = dat_gainloss$obs %>%
    mutate(
      change = if_else(change == "increase", "increase", "no clear change"),
      complete_change = if_else(complete_change == "new", "new", NA)
    ),
  dat_niche, onesite = "elkhorn"
)$circle
gg_gainloss_elkhorn4 <- plot_species_gainloss_obs(
  obs_tbl = dat_gainloss$obs %>%
    mutate(complete_change = if_else(complete_change == "new", "new", NA)),
  dat_niche, onesite = "elkhorn"
)$circle
gg_gainloss_elkhorn5 <- plot_species_gainloss_obs(obs_tbl = dat_gainloss$obs, dat_niche, onesite = "elkhorn")$circle

Across the observations, species gained in communities by significantly increasing abundance over time (e.g., Bromus diandrus) or recruitment (appeared only after the 5th yr, e.g., Eschscholzia californica); in contrast, species lost from communities by significantly decreasing abundance over time (e.g., Festuca myuros) or extirpation (disappeared in the last 5 yr, e.g., Hypochaeris radicata). In the experiment, species did not experience complete turnover, but some gained by being more abundant (e.g., Brachypodium distachyon), while some lost by being less abundant (e.g., Torilis arvensis) in warming compared to ambient plots.

Synthesize community shifts in observation and experiments

dat_shift <- calc_community_shift(dat_index = dat_index)
usethis::use_data(dat_shift, overwrite = T)
gg_community_shift <- plot_community_shift(dat_shift, dat_niche)
gg_community_shift$combined

Due to the high correlation of species temperature and precipitation niches, CTI and CPI shifts at the community level appear highly coupled.

df_summ_shift_coupling <- summ_shift_coupling(dat_shift)
df_summ_shift_coupling
#> # A tibble: 4  6
#>   ratio      group         median      min    max scale_factor
#>   <chr>      <fct>          <dbl>    <dbl>  <dbl>        <dbl>
#> 1 cpi_to_cti Observation -12.3    -156.     9.94           0.1
#> 2 cpi_to_cti Experiment   -9.28    -23.8   40.1            0.1
#> 3 cti_to_cpi Observation  -0.0666   -0.124  0.222         10  
#> 4 cti_to_cpi Experiment   -0.0970   -0.128  0.223         10

A community thermophilization of 0.1 C corresponded to a xerophilization of -12.3 mm from the observations and -9.28 mm from the experiment. Likewise, a community xerophilization of -10 mm corresponded to a thermophilization of 0.0666 C from the observations and 0.097 C from the experiment.
